kward\n\nr\nSAGE AND SULPHUR.\nMade Her Look Twenty Years Younger\nREAD MRS. HERRICK'S SWORN STATEMENT\nState of New York\n1 County oy Monroe\nNancy A. Herrick, being duly sworn, depos and says: When\nI was a girl, I had a head of heavy, long, dark brown hair which\n.was the envy of my schoolmates, and which attracted the atten\ntion and remarks of strangers. As I grew older, my hair com\nmenced to come out, just a little at first, but gradually more and\nmore, and then began to turn gray. 1 was induced by the many\ngood reports I had heard of Wyeth's $age and Sulphur Hair\nRemedy to try a bottle. My hair was quite thin and .gray when\nI began using Sage and Sulphur, and you can hnrgirrrrnnj' satis\nfaction when I found that it was fast coming Wtk'fiO Rt Mtural\ncondition, being thicker, darker and more glossy th\u00bb It had been\nfor a long time. I continued to use Sage and Sulphur, and nqr\nhair is now as heavy, dark and smooth as when I was a gM ft!\nsixteen. It is now four years since I commenced using Saga dd\nSulphur, and my hair is still in splendid condition.\nRochester, N. Y.\nss\n/i\n>4\nit -1\nIT\nhrfert W\u00bb IkM\n\n\nkfmi\nJ\nr\nsaWsKi\nPreserve Your Youth and Beauty by Using\n\nIk\nWYETH'S\nSAGE^SULPH u r\nHAIR R E M E D Y_\nIt Is Pure, Safe And Reliable\nIi Is Not Sticky. Oily Or Greasy\nIt Is An Elegant, Refreshing Dressing\nIt Makes The Hair Soft And Glossy\nIt Quickly Removes Dandruff __\nIt Restores I -ed And Gray Hair To Natural Colof/J\nIt Stops Hair Falling And Makes The Hair Grow\ni\nI\nH Will Make You Look Years Younger\nPRICE\niOc. and $1\nA BOTTLE\n\nWYETH\nCHEMICAL\nCOMPANY\n74 Cortlandt St.\nNEW YORK. N. Y.\nAT ALL DRUGGISTS\nU Tear Druggist Does Not Keep It.\nSend On The Fries la Stamps, And\nn\nWe W1U Scad Vos A Lars* Bom*.\nExpress Prepaid.\nFor Sale and Recommended by\n\nilL\nbe taken into the case. The last ac\ntion has been requested by the Nation\nal Woman's Suffrage Association,\nwhich intends that the case shall be\nin the hands of the women themselves\nInstead of the male sex.\nNOTICE FOR PUBLICATION.\nDepartment of the Interior, U. S. Land\nOffice at Jackson, Mississippi, July 23,\nmo.\nNotice Is hereby given that Cad H.\nYoung, of Hattiesburg, Miss., R. F. D.\nNo. 2, who, on June 23, 1903, made\nHomestead Entry No. 38,390, sereal\nNo. 01,402, for the N. E'. qr. of the N.\n,K. qr., Section 14, Township 4 North,\nRange 12 West, St. Stephens Meridian.\nA. F., to the N. W. qr. of the N. E. qr.,\nSection 14, Township 4 North, Range\n12 West, has filed notlca of his inten\ntion to make final five-year proof, to\nestablish claim to the land above de\nscribed, before the Clerk of the Cir\ncuit Court of Forrest County, at Hat\ntiesburg, Miss., on the 3d day of Sep\ntember, 1910.\nClaimant names as witnesses: J.\nA. McCardle, A. C. Gay, W. L. Carter,\nJ. W. Evans, all of Hattiesburg, Miss.,\nR. F. D. No. 2.\n\nJ. JAY WHITE. Register.\n20-5 Mons.\nNOTICE\nOur tank wagon is making dally\ntrips with fresh spring water. We de\nsire to ask our patrons to assist in\nmaking deliveries, by stopping the\nj driver when he fails to stop at your\ni bouse. Our business is rapidly ln\nI creasing and while we have a tank\nholding 205 gallons\u2014It rushes our\nteam and driver to deliver everyone\nwater before noon, and it is possible\nthat some will not receive their water\nbefore one or two o'clock.\nParties falling to get their water\nw jjj confer quite a favor on the man\nagement by telephoning us over either\nphone numbers, 217 or 917-!#rlng.\nADVERTISE IN THE DAILY NEWS.\n\nRespectfully,\nMammoth Mineral Springs Hotel Co.\nMammoth Springs, Miss.\nl-2t\nBANKER CLEWS REVIEWS\nSpecial to The yews.\nNew York, Aug. 1.\u2014The breakdown\nof a speculative clique, which sought\nto link up a reries of disconnected\nlines into a new transcontinental' sys\ntem, proved to be at tho bottom of\ncollapse in values which occurred In\nMonday's and Tuesday's market. The\ntaking over of these securities by a\nstrong International banking syndi\ncate unquestionably saved the market\nfrom a worse crash, and produced a\nradical change for the better in the\ntechnical situation. As soon as the\nfacts became known liquidation\nceased, and a sharp rebound followed\nwhich was materially accelerated by\na rush to cover outstanding shorts.\nThe extreme pessimism bred by the\nmysterious declines of last week sud\ndenly disappeared and the whole mar\nket displayed a better and more nor\nmal tone. Another consideration\nwhich imparted a better tone and\nchecked the growing wave of pessim\nism was the report of the United\nStates Steel Co., which showed hand\nsome profits for the past quarter and\na smaller falling off in orders on band\nthan was really anticipated. As the\nsteel trade Is still considered one of\nthe best Industrial barbometers, the\neffect of this report was naturally\nstimulating.\nMonetary Situation.\nThe monetary situation allows fur\nther Improvement,\nsources continue to rise, and there Is\nmuch less apprehension of severe\nmonetary stringency during the com\ning fall than at one time existed.\nWhat with liquidation In stocks and\ndeclining values in commodities and\nsecurities, money goes much further\nthan six months ago, especially in view\nof the shrinkage In volume cf business\nand speculation. The last statement\nof the national banks may have been\nunsatisfactory owing to the small\ncontraction In loans at the Interior,\nbut recently farmers have been mar\nketing their crops more freely and\nliquidation from this and other sourc\nes will probably result In a much bet\nter showing for the Interior banks\nwhen the next call is Issued.\nImports continue on an Increasing\nscale, and there Is every Indication\nthat we will command all of the\npreciOHS metal that we need,\nrope's heavy Investments In our se\ncurities during the past six months\nmore than offset the shrinkage In our\nforeign trade balance. The tendency\nIn our foreign trade Is towards Im\nprovement. because the decline in\ncommodities puts us upon a more fav\norable export basis and tends to re\nstrain Importations,\nstringency may be anticipated during\nthe crop season, there Is much less\ndanger of a crisis In this respect than\nformerly. Should any of the bankers\nLocal bank re\nGold\nEu\nWhile some\nagree to form currency associations\nthat will\nbe a further protection\nagainst a crisis, which In view of the\nInability of the Government to assist\nthe market Id an emergency would\nseem to be a desirable alternative. No\none prgtunds that these associations\nare ataUcnre 'or our currency evils,\nbut they would at east prove an ef\npaBiatfre until genuine cur\nBclelin\nrency ret\n'd\nThe Crop OuMawk.\nThe crop outlook Is net s n dra ta\nsatisfactory. The yield of wheat, oak\nton and corn is likely to fall bellm\nearly calculations. The loss In wheat\nhas already been amply discounted\nand la not serious. Much deteriora\ntion, however, has taken place In cot\nton, and the corn crop has likewise\nlost ground to some extent Both of\nthese crops are still In danger of\nearly frosts, and disaster to either\nwould, under present conditions, have\na very serious effect upon business.\nThe country was urgently In need of\na large cotton crop but the outlook is\nnow for a 12,000,000 bale yield, which\nIs below normal and means continued\nhigh prices for cotton. The effect of\nthis upon the domestic industry and\nupon our export trade must be taken\nInto consideration.\nOur main hope\nregarding the crops still centcrc upon\ncorn. Should this prove r. boBM\nyield It will do much townrda\nting any loss in wheat and nnttefr.\nThe result, however, will be\nthe agricultural\nSome of our farmers will enjo\ner season of exceptional profit\n\nsituation\nothers must endure serious lojWjjTJ\nBusiness Outlook.\nThe business outlook Is mtxflH\nbright and doubtful in spots. SA\nconservative disposition existflfl\nthose who lead in both rorsjH\nand Industrial affairs. Reac^|\nbegun with varying force In\nIndustries. Values had beei^l\nand f t la\nthat Industrial interests of the coun\ntry must face some readjustment.\nThis process Js unpleasant while It\ncontinues, but will in the end leave\nboth commerce and industry upon a\nsounder and stronger basis. The re\naction which began in stocks must\nextend more or less into other divis\nions of business,\nthe stock market has fully discounted\nany Industrial depression. This Is so\nregarding the railroads at least, for\nthe latter having various resources\nalways suffer less in business depres\nsion than individual industries. More\nover, the railroads are confidently\nlooking forward to permission from\nthe Interstate Commissioners to ad\nvance freight rates later on.\nIn all probability\nPolitics.\nAs for the political outlook, that is\nstill unsettled. The fall campaign is\njust beginning and may develop dis\nturbing Influences. At the same time\nboth Government officials and local\npoliticians are beginning to learn that\nblind attacks upon capital are quite\nlikely to injure their own prospects\nas well as those of their party. There\nhas been a decided toning down of\nhostility towards corporations, which\nbetokens more rational treatment of\nthe latter In the future.\nThe market has now had a sharp\nrally and on any further advance the\ntaking of profits would be In order.\nThe big banking interests are showing\nmore confidence in the future and\nseem willing to express tjielr belief in\nthe general soundness of the present\nfinancial situation, though not in\nclined to support any prolonged bull\nmovement. In such quarters the\npresent situation as to the business\nand crop outlook is well understood,\nand no disposition is shown to finance\nany great stock market activity until\nthe monetary and political outlook is\nclarified. So far as Wall Street is\nconcerned the outlook has Improved,\nand the Indications point to a much\nbetter market. Securities bought on\nconservative lines are likely to prove\nprofitable investments. Stocks have\nsuffered a shrinkage of nearly $2,000,\n000,000 during the past six months and\nare fairly entitled to a substantial\nrecovery.\n000\nm\n0\nPOISON\nBone Pains,\nUlcers, Scaly\nSkin, Pimples.\nB. B. B. Cures Above Troubles, Also\nEczema and Rheumatism. Test B\nB. B.\nFor twenty-five years Botanic Blood\nBalm (B. B. B.), has been curing year\nly thousands of sufferers from Pri\nmary, Secondary or Tertiary Blooa\nPoison, and all forms of Blood and\nSkin Diseases, Cancer, Rheumatism\nand Eczema. We solicit the most ob\nstinate cases, because B. B. B. cures\nwhere all else fails. If you have\naches and pains In Bones, Back or\nJoints, Mucus Patches in mouth. Sore\nThroat, Pimples, Copper-Colored Spots\nDicers or any part of the body, hair\nor eyebrows falling out. Itching, wa\ntery blisters or open humors, Risings\nIf Staples \u00b0f Kciema. Bolls, Swellings\nPjMfiMnM. take B. B. B. It kills the\nfOlafd TT 1 the Mood pure and rich.\nchanging the entire body\nhealthy cendltlon, healing\nevermore or pimple and stopping all\naches pains and itching, curing the\nworst case of Blood Poison, Rheuma\ntism or Eczema.\nBOTANIC BLOOD BALM, (a B. B.)\nIs pleasant and safe to take; composed\nof pure Botanic ingredients. It puri\nfies and enriches the blood.\nDRUGGISTS, $1 PER LARGE BOT\nTLE, with directions for home cure.\nlnt\nThis coupon cut from Hatties\nburg News Is good for one sample\njf B. B. B. mailed free in plain\npackage. Simply fill In your name\nand address on dotted lines below\nand mail to BLOOD BALM CO.,\nAtlanta, Ga.\n\u2022V\nState name of trouble, If you know.\nVeterinary Surgeon and Dentist\nManufacturer of Harthlll'a*Hy\npodermlc Injection for oollc, foun\nder or laminltls, vartsgo or stag\ngera.\nOFFICE AT POLK'S STABLE.\nCumb. Phone MB; Homs Phone\nPURELY\n\u2022VEGETABLE\nm\nIt is a generally recognized fact that medicines taken\nfrom the botanical kingdom are better adapted to the\ndelicate human system, and safer in every way, than\nthose composed of strong mineral mixtures,\nIn the early settlement of this land, our forefathers\nwere obliged to procure their medicines from Nature s\ngreat laboratories of forest and field. They searched out\nand compounded the different vegetable materials into\nteas, concoctions and medicines. That these pioneers\nfound the most potent and valuable of the roots, herbs\nand barks placed at their disposal, is abundantly proven\nby the fact that the great majority of them were blessed\nwith rugged health. They cured their diseases and were\nenabled to do the great preliminary work of civilization\nbecause the remedies they used were Nature's remedies,\nand specially adapted to the needs of humanity.\nAmong the very best of these vegetable preparations is S. S. S., a medi\ncine made entirely of roots, herbs and barks in such combination as to make\nit the greatest of all blood purifiers and\nthe finest of all tonics. S. S. S. does\nnot contain the least particle of min\neral in any form, and is absolutely a\nsafe medicine for any one to use.\nWhile purifying the blood this\ngreat vegetable remedy'builds up and\nstrengthens every portion of the sys\ntem. S. S. S. cures Rheumatism, Ca\ntarrh, Sores and Ulcers, Malaria, Scrof\nula, Skin Diseases, Contagious Blood\nPoison, hereditary taints, and all other\ndiseases and disorders caused by im\npure or polluted blood.\nAs a tonic S. S. S. is uneqalled. It\nInvigorates every portion of the system,\nand the healthy blood it creates largely\nassists in overcoming any derangement of the digestive system. If you are\nsuffering from any blood trouble, or need a tonic to build up your consti\ntution, you could not do better than to take S. S. S., a medicine that is in\nno degree harmful. Book on the blood and any medical advice free.\nTHE SWIFT SPECIFIC CO., ATLAHTA, GA.\nCHEMIST FOUND S.S.S. FREE\nFROM MINERALS.\nA few years afo I was taken\nwith Inflammatory Rheumatism.\nUpon the advice of a friend I de\ncided to try 8.8.8. Before allow\ning me to take it, however, my\nfftiardian, who was a chemist, an\nalysed the remedy, and pro\nnounced it free from potash or\nmercury. X continued the remedy,\nand in two months I was cured\ncompletely. The cure waa perma\nnent, for I have never sinee had a\ntouch of Rheumatism, thougrh\nmany times exposed to damp and\ncold weather.\nMRS. ELEANOR T. JONES,\n68 Gliff 8t., Roxbury, Mass.\nLAUNDRI\u00a3RS, CLEANERS <81 PRESSERS\n'li!\nOUR LAUNDRY WORK,\nlc sure to make a satisfactory Im\npression at first wearing. Get the\nhabit, and yon will find you cannot\ndo without it Your linen la always\nfresh, clean, shapely sad comforta\nble. No rougn edges, torn button\nholes or other annoyances. Com\nyp\\ I r-A-ltti\nt j mence the New Year by getting ac\n\"'\u2014-A\nqualnted with us. You will find us\nwell worth cultivating.\n\n\u2022v*\na.\n\n\ny\nm\nCK\nP\n\u00a33\nI\nPhoenix Laundry\nBoth Phono\u201436\nr\n200, 202, 204 and 20S Main BL\nSPECIAL RATES\n\u25a0AND\nSPECIAL TRAIN\nAgricultural Boll Weevil Day\nAT\nMcNEIL, MISSISSIPPI\nState Agricultural Experiment Station\nvia.\nMississippi Central Railroad\nHattiesburg&New Orleans&Northeastern R. R.\nWEDNESDAY, AUG. 3, 1910.\nStations\nFare for\nRound Trip\nSchedule\nLeave Natchez\nLeave Roxie.\nLeave Rrookhaven\nLeave Wanllla\nLeave Silver Creek\nArrive Hattiesburg\nArrive McNeill.\n4:30 a. m.\n.5:18 a. m.\n6:59 a. m.\n7:41a.m.\n8:01 a. m.\n.10:10 a. m.\n...12:00M.\n2.00\n2.00\n2.00\n1.75\n1.75\nReturning special train will leave McNeill Station at 6:00 p.\nWednesday, August 3rd.\nm.\nThis train will be run ih order to enable the farmers and business\npeople along the Mississippi Central to visit the State Experiment\nFarm at McNeill and return same day.\nThe numerous experiments at this farm are of Incalculable value\nto South Mississippi residents, but must be seen to be of benefit. Man\nager E. B. Ferris not only keeps records to explain everything but can\ntell and show you how to accomplish best results in cultivation of\nproducts of the soil In this section.\nGrowing Corn, Cotton. Hay, Cane (for syrup). Truck, Fruit and\nDairying Is conspicuously emphasized. Cane syrup Is made and canned\nhere by the latest Improved methods.\nBASKET DINNER.\nIt has been suggested that this occa ilon be made a basket dinner\npicnic. Every family who wishes to do to Is Invited to bring along a\nbasket of provisions. Tie tag with your ^uame to handle of basket\nand deliver to baggage car door when train Btops. Someone will be fn\nthe car to take care of it free of chargw. Bring your wires and sweet\nhearts and make a royal picnic of the day.\nThose taking baskets will have dlnnei on the ground in one of\nthe beautiful groves at the Experiment Farm a short distance from, and\nIn sight of the railroad depot.\n2.00 P. M _ SPEAKING\u20142:00 P. M.\nFollowing dinner on the ground there will be Just one addreee.\nHon. B. L. Moss, of the Department of Agriculture, U. S. Government,\nhas consented to be on hand and make some remarks and practical sug\ngestions on ways and means of combatting thy .boll\nAt the conclusion of the speaking the grL fy will be show over the I]\nfarm, and the methods of the experts win he tally explained. 11\nFor further information aae local mMT or address,\nR. D. REEVES, n~imillBll. fimall\ni","height":"17328","width":"14232"}}
